<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1469,1710]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1469,1494]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Swimming setae present or absent; posterior suture lines of Cx-IV extending more posteriorly to partially enclose the genital field.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1469,1710]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1541,1566]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Remarks</emphasis>
: Probably a monophyletic clade early split off from the north-hemispheric nominate subgenus. Characterized in first line by the different shape of the posteromedial suture of Cx-IV. The two species included differ also remarkably from each other (see discussion of 
<taxonomicName box="[812,1047,1613,1638]" class="Arachnida" family="Mideopsidae" genus="Xystonotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="madagascariensis">
<emphasis box="[812,1047,1613,1638]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">X. madagascariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) suggesting an early evolutionary separation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1401,1685,1710]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1469,1710]" box="[199,1401,1685,1710]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1685,1710]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Distribution</emphasis>
: Southern African region with one species from 
<collectingCountry box="[892,1027,1685,1710]" name="Madagascar" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
and the other from 
<collectingCountry box="[1249,1396,1685,1710]" name="South Africa" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">South Africa</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
